  "prompt": "Around what time did humans start naming each other?",
  "response": "It's difficult to pinpoint exactly when humans first started naming each other, but anthropologists believe that the practice of using personal names likely emerged with the development of complex language and social structures. This would have occurred during the Upper Paleolithic period, roughly 40,000 to 50,000 years ago, when modern human cognition and communication skills were evolving.\n\nEarly names were probably descriptive, based on personal characteristics, skills, or roles within a community. As human societies became more complex, naming practices became more formalized. The earliest written evidence of personal names dates back to around 3400-3000 BCE in ancient Mesopotamia, with the development of cuneiform writing.\n\nWhile we can't know precisely when the first personal names were used, it's reasonable to assume that humans were naming each other long before they developed writing systems, as names are crucial for social interaction and identification within a group.",
